The paper discusses pseudorandom generators (PRGs) for Lipschitz functions of low-degree polynomials, which are relevant to the study of polynomial threshold functions and have applications in graph theory and optimization. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.CC (computational complexity), cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.IT (information theory), cs.LG (machine learning), and cs.NA (numerical analysis). Among these, cs.CC and cs.DS seem to be the most likely categories, as the paper deals with the complexity of generating pseudorandom numbers and the design of efficient algorithms for graph optimization problems. However, cs.IT, cs.LG, and cs.NA are also possible categories, as the paper involves the analysis of Lipschitz functions, which is related to information theory and machine learning, as well as the use of semi-definite programming, which is a numerical optimization technique.
